00:46:44.838 --> 00:46:48.501
He will wear wool when he fulfills

00:46:48.740 --> 00:46:49.961
Passover as the lamb.

00:46:50.862 --> 00:46:53.144
He will wear linen when he fulfills Yom

00:46:53.184 --> 00:46:53.664
Kipurym.

00:46:54.637 --> 00:46:57.581
as the returning king and high priest.

00:46:58.503 --> 00:46:59.364
He will do both.

00:47:00.547 --> 00:47:06.335
And it is likely that her husband will

00:47:07.719 --> 00:47:09.121
be adorned in linen.

00:47:09.766 --> 00:47:12.829
I don't think so much in wool.

00:47:13.451 --> 00:47:16.954
I don't know what the hides are to

00:47:17.014 --> 00:47:19.438
depict the bullish metaphor.

00:47:19.818 --> 00:47:20.217
But again,

00:47:20.259 --> 00:47:22.320
the bullish metaphor that Yahowah uses

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:26.465
really is to be symbolic of the man's

00:47:26.505 --> 00:47:27.907
disposition and character.

00:47:30.068 --> 00:47:31.389
Don't stand in his way.

00:47:31.429 --> 00:47:36.630
There are three men depicted as animals,

00:47:37.449 --> 00:47:38.710
not because they're animals,

00:47:38.769 --> 00:47:41.110
but because there's a characteristic of

00:47:41.170 --> 00:47:43.550
each of those animals that is conveyed

00:47:43.590 --> 00:47:45.411
through their personality that he wants

00:47:45.452 --> 00:47:46.231
people to know.

00:47:46.771 --> 00:47:48.472
A Dowd as the ram,

00:47:48.492 --> 00:47:50.472
the leader of the flock,

00:47:50.913 --> 00:47:54.393
but also as one who is as vulnerable

00:47:55.353 --> 00:47:55.934
as a lamb.

00:47:57.858 --> 00:47:59.159
when enduring Passover.

00:48:00.221 --> 00:48:02.161
And he wants Dowd known as this,

00:48:02.181 --> 00:48:05.224
that there probably is no other animal

00:48:05.284 --> 00:48:09.547
